CloudWatch Logs.

Logs are the unstructured cousin of metrics, text lines from services and applications, collected and queryable. The hierarchy has three levels. A log group is the container, one per logical source, with a retention setting from one day to ten years, or never expire. A log stream is the events from a single emitter, one Lambda execution environment, one E-C-2 instance, one container. And log events are the actual timestamped lines.

Lots of sources land here automatically. Lambda writes to slash-a-w-s-slash-lambda-slash the function name. E-C-S captures container standard-out and standard-error. A-P-I Gateway has access logs, and V-P-C Flow Logs, Route 53 query logs, CloudTrail, and the CloudWatch Agent all deliver here too.

Two features turn logs into action. A metric filter scans incoming log events for a pattern and increments a CloudWatch metric when it matches; the canonical pattern is a filter like question-mark-ERROR question-mark-Exception on an application log group, which emits an ApplicationErrors metric, and then an alarm on that metric pages you. That's how you turn unstructured text into actionable signals. Beyond that, CloudWatch Logs Insights gives you a S-Q-L-like query language, with fields, filter, and stats-by, to search across log groups ad-hoc, the tool for grepping production logs without S-S-H-ing anywhere. And a subscription filter streams matching log events in real time to OpenSearch, Lambda, or Kinesis, for downstream processing or a third-party S-I-E-M like Splunk.
